\f0\b\fs48 \cf2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Architectural Framework for Secure Intent: Implementing Hardware-Backed Biometric Non-Repudiation in Hybrid iOS Applications\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The transition from traditional digital signatures to hardware-fortified biometric authentication represents a significant shift in the landscape of mobile security and legal non-repudiation. For applications such as the Pakt NDA platform, which require verifiable proof of user intent, the standard biometric "unlock" is often insufficient. The requirement for the "Confirm with Side Button" interaction\'97formally known within the Apple ecosystem as Secure Intent\'97introduces a physical layer of security that establishes a direct link between the human user and the device's Secure Enclave. This report provides an exhaustive technical analysis of the native frameworks, hybrid bridge implementations, and cryptographic attestation protocols required to deliver this specific confirmatory experience while ensuring legal enforceability.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 The Evolution and Hardware Foundations of Secure Intent\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 To understand the implementation of the "Confirm with Side Button" experience, one must first analyze the underlying architecture of Apple's Trusted Execution Environment (TEE). Secure Intent is not a software-based user interface trick but a hardware-enforced state machine designed to prevent "look-to-confirm" errors and spoofing attacks. On devices equipped with Face ID, the risk of accidental authorization is heightened because the biometric sensor operates passively; merely looking at the device can trigger a match. To mitigate this, Apple introduced the physical double-press requirement for high-value operations such as Apple Pay transactions and App Store purchases.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 The Secure Enclave and Physical Hardware Interrupts\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The Secure Enclave is a dedicated subsystem integrated into Apple\'92s System on a Chip (SoC), isolated from the main Application Processor (AP) to provide an additional layer of security even if the kernel is compromised. The Secure Enclave Processor (SEP) runs its own customized version of the L4 microkernel and manages its own Boot ROM, a hardware-based True Random Number Generator (TRNG), and a dedicated AES engine.\

