\cf2 For third-party applications, the "Confirm with Side Button" UI is traditionally a system-managed experience triggered by the \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 Security\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  framework when a key has the \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 .privateKeyUsage\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  constraint combined with specific system-level policies. However, there is a critical distinction: the exact UI used by the App Store and Apple Pay is part of a "high-trust" system sheet. For a third-party app to trigger a similar interaction for document signing, it must generate a hardware-bound key and call \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 SecKeyCreateSignature\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 The Implementation of ECDSA Signing in the Secure Enclave\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The Pakt application's signing process should involve the creation of a NIST P-256 elliptic curve key pair. The private key is generated and stored permanently within the Secure Enclave, while only the public key is ever exposed to the application.\
