\fs24 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 When the user is ready to sign the NDA, the application must provide a hash of the document to the Secure Enclave for signing. This operation triggers the biometric authentication prompt. If the system policy determines that the context requires Secure Intent, it may present the confirmatory UI. It is important to note that as of iOS 18.1, Apple has opened the NFC and Secure Element Platform to third-party developers, which provides a more direct way to utilize the "double-click" gesture for authorized transactions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Capacitor Integration: Bridging Web and Native Security\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 Since Pakt is a React application wrapped in Capacitor, the web layer cannot directly call the \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 Security.framework\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  or \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 LocalAuthentication\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  APIs. A native bridge or a specialized plugin is required to expose these capabilities to the JavaScript runtime.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Plugin Selection for Secure Signing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The standard \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 @capacitor/biometric-auth\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  plugin is generally optimized for user login scenarios (returning a boolean success) and may not provide the low-level Secure Enclave key management required for legal NDA signing. For Pakt's specific needs, the \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 @perfood/capacitor-crypto-api\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  is a more robust choice, as it is designed for cryptographic authentication using hardware-backed keys.\

