\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Fallback Strategies and UI Discrepancies\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 If the specific "Confirm with Side Button" animation is restricted to Apple's own system flows (like Apple Pay), the app must employ the closest possible alternative. In native third-party apps, the \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 LAContext\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  biometric prompt is the standard. While it lacks the double-press requirement, it remains a robust form of identity verification.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Differences in User Experience\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The difference between the App Store experience and a third-party biometric prompt is primarily one of "active" versus "passive" confirmation.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 App Store / Apple Pay
\f1\b0 : Requires a deliberate physical gesture (double-press) followed by a Face ID scan. This is used for "Intent to Pay" or "Intent to Install".\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Standard LAContext
\f1\b0 : Only requires the Face ID scan. This is used for "Identity Verification" or "Login".\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 LAContext\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  prompt can be customized with a \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 localizedReason\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  string, which appears as a subtitle in the dialog. For Pakt, this reason should be explicit: "Please authenticate to sign the Pakt NDA and verify your identity."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 Mimicking High-Trust Interfaces\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 To bridge the gap in user perception, the Pakt app can implement a "confirmation sheet" in the React UI that mimics the layout of the Apple Pay sheet. This sheet should explain to the user that they are about to perform a hardware-secured signing operation. Once the user clicks a "Sign Now" button in the web UI, the app triggers the native Face ID prompt. This two-step process (React confirmation + Native biometric scan) provides a similar UX to the system's own confirmatory flows.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 Cross-Device Flow and Relay Hardening\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 The cross-device pattern (Party A displays a QR, Party B scans and authenticates) is inherently susceptible to relay attacks. The Pakt app currently uses Firebase Realtime Database as a relay, where Party B writes a result and Party A listens. This pattern must be hardened using a challenge-response mechanism.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 The Cryptographic Challenge-Response Pattern\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 Instead of Party B writing a "Success" flag, the interaction should follow a formal cryptographic protocol:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Challenge Generation
\f1\b0 : Party A's app requests a random nonce (challenge) from the Pakt server.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 QR Presentation
\f1\b0 : Party A displays a QR code containing the session ID and the challenge.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Authentication
\f1\b0 : Party B scans the QR, performs the Face ID/Secure Intent signing on the challenge, and generates a signature.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Relay
\f1\b0 : Party B writes the signature and their \cf6 \cb7 \strokec6 App Attest\cf2 \cb1 \strokec2  assertion to the Firebase relay.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Final Verification
\f1\b0 : The Pakt server (not Party A's app) verifies the signature against Party B's public key and ensures the challenge matches. Only then is the relay considered complete.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 This ensures that even if an attacker intercepts the Firebase traffic, they cannot "fake" a successful signature without the physical device and the owner's biometric presence.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

